vices/Legal](https://asianbusinessreview.com/professional-serviceslegal)\n\n[Residential](https://asianbusinessreview.com/residential)\n\n[Residential Property](https://asianbusinessreview.com/residential-property)\n\n[Retail](https://asianbusinessreview.com/retail)\n\n[Retail Banking](https://asianbusinessreview.com/retail-banking)\n\n[Shipping & Marine](https://asianbusinessreview.com/shipping-marine)\n\n[Stocks](https://asianbusinessreview.com/stocks)\n\n[Telecom & Internet](https://asianbusinessreview.com/telecom-internet)\n\n[Transport & Logistics](https://asianbusinessreview.com/transport-logistics)\n\n[Utilities](https://asianbusinessreview.com/utilities)\n\nThere are no upcoming [events](/events) found. Please try again later.\n\n\n\n\n[News](https://asianbusinessreview.com/news)\n\n[Insurance](https://asianbusinessreview.com/insurance)\n\nStaff Reporter\n\n,   [Taiwan](https://asianbusinessreview.com/market/taiwan)\n\nPublished:\n\n/Li Lin from Unsplash\n\n# Taiwan’s insurance premiums rise 8% as claims outpace non-life growth in 2025\n\n**Non-life payouts climb faster than premiums, signalling pressure on underwriting margins.**\n\n[Taiwan](https://insuranceasia.com/market/taiwan)’s insurance sector total premium income reached $93.1b (NT$2.91t) in 2025, up 7.35% year-on-year (YoY).\n\n[Life insurance](https://insuranceasia.com/topics/life-insurance) continued to dominate the market, contributing $83.8b (NT$2.62t), whilst non-life insurance accounted for $9.2b (NT$286.8b), according to data released by the Financial Supervisory Commission’s Insurance Bureau.\n\n[Non-life](https://insuranceasia.com/topics/general-insurance) insurance premiums grew 5.67% YoY to $9.2b (NT$286.8b). Motor insurance remained the largest segment, generating $4.5b (NT$139.4b), followed by accident insurance at $2.9b (NT$89.5b). Claims in the non-life segment rose 8.10% YoY to $4.0b (NT$125.8b) for the year.\n\nLife insurance premiums increased 7.53% YoY to $83.8b (NT$2.62t). Individual life policies made up the largest share at $57.0b (NT$1.78t), followed by health insurance at $14.7b (NT$459.2b) and annuities at $9.0b (NT$282.3b).\n\nThe industry’s total assets reached $1.2t (NT$38.27t) in 2025, compared with $1.2t (NT$37.43t) in 2024. Insurance assets accounted for 32.91% of total financial sector assets, slightly lower than 33.34% a year earlier.\n\nOverall, the insurance sector reported stable profitability. Non-life insurers posted net income of $1.0b (NT$31.1b), whilst life insurers recorded $5.8b (NT$180.8b) in net income.\n\nInsurance penetration, measured as premiums as a share of GDP, stood at 10.14% YoY in 2025, down slightly from 10.54% YoY in 2024. Insurance density, or per capita premium spending, rose to $3,997.8 (NT$124,931).\n\nThe number of insurance companies remained stable at 51, with 3 reinsurers and 20 offshore insurance units.\n\nThe industry employed about 400,908 people in 2024, with a slight decline in recent years.\n\n*($1.00 = NT$31.53)*\n\n## Follow the link s for more news on\n\n[General insurance](https://asianbusinessreview.com/topics/general-insurance)\n\n[insurance](https://asianbusinessreview.com/topics/insurance)\n\n[Life insurance](https://asianbusinessreview.com/topics/life-insurance)\n\n## Also Read\n\n### [Asia’s marine insurers face rising losses from climate labour risks](https://asianbusinessreview.com/insurance/in-focus/asias-marine-insurers-face-rising-losses-climate-labour-risks)\n\n### [Insurers face capacity strain as $300b data centre boom grows](https://asianbusinessreview.com/insurance/news/insurers-face-capacity-strain-300b-data-centre-boom-grows)\n\nJoin Asian Business Review community\n\nSince you're here...\n\n...there are many ways you can work with us to advertise your company and connect to your customers. Our team can help you design and create an advertising campaign, in print and digital, on this website and in print magazine.\n\nWe can also organize a real life or digital event f