st\n\nThe burgeoning [data centre](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/topics/techtalk/artificial-intelligence) insurance market represents a “huge growth opportunity”, with some $10bn (£7.5bn) in new insurance premiums forecast for 2026.\n\n**Read: [Cyber risk firm warns insurers not to view AI simply as ‘risk multiplier’](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/news/cyber-risk-firm-warns-insurers-not-to-view-ai-simply-as-risk-multiplier/1458260.article)**\n\n**Read: [Lancashire inks deal to use Novee’s AI proposition for power and renewables underwriting](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/news/lancashire-inks-deal-to-use-novees-ai-proposition-for-power-and-renewables-underwriting/1456866.article)**\n\nNot subscribed? [Become a subscriber and access our premium content](https://account.insurancetimes.co.uk/subscribe?sourcecode=ITStandard18&campaigncode=ITSUBIA&returl=https%3a%2f%2fwww.insurancetimes.co.uk)\n\n**Explore more [artificial intelligence related stories here](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/topics/artificial-intelligence), or discover other [news stories here](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/news)**\n\nThe figure represents a vast new risk pool, dwarfing the annual premiums of approximately $5bn (£3.8bn) seen in the global aviation industry.\n\nThis insight comes from a new report by S&P Global Ratings, released today (14 April 2026), which highlighted that a complex ecosystem of developers, builders, utility providers and equity investors will offer multiple vectors for [insurers](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/insurers) to provide cover.\n\nAnd with [annual global investment](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/topics/financial-/-results) in data centres likely to surpass $300bn (£230bn) by 2027, the opportunities for (re)insurers will continue to grow.\n\nHowever, S&P Global Ratings highlighted that capacity constraints are likely to become a limiting factor for insurer involvement, due to the high insurable value of individual projects.\n\n### Capacity constraints\n\nCharles-Marie Delpuech, credit analyst at S&P Global Ratings, said: “We expect capacity constraints to limit the industry’s ability to fully insure these hyperscale data centre projects, as total insurable values reach $20bn (£15bn) to $30bn (£22.5bn) per location.\n\n**Read: [Millions spent on insurance AI with little to show for it](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/news/millions-spent-on-insurance-ai-with-little-to-show-for-it/1458183.article)**\n\n**Read: [Novee AI secures £1.6m in funding to enhance commercial and specialty underwriting](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/news/novee-ai-secures-16m-in-funding-to-enhance-commercial-and-specialty-underwriting/1455913.article)**\n\n**Explore more [artificial intelligence related stories here](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/topics/artificial-intelligence), or discover other [news stories here](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/news)**\n\n“How (re)insurers manage concentration and aggregation risk due to the colocation of high-value assets and the interconnectedness of risks through the presence of multiple stakeholders will be a key consideration in our credit rating analysis.”\n\n[George McDade](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/george-mcdade/2313.bio)\n\n* Follow\n\nGeorge is a data reporter at Insurance Times, uncovering interesting industry trends and reporting on the technological advancements that will shape the future of the sector.  \n  \nHe graduated in 2017 from the University of Manchester with a degree in Geology. He spent the first part of his career working in consulting and tech, spending time at Citibank as a data analyst, before working as an analytics engineer with clients in the retail, technology, manufacturing and financial services sectors.[View full Profile](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/george-mcdade/2313.bio)\n\n## [More George McDade](https://www.insurancetimes.co.uk/george-mcdade/2313.bio)\n\n* ## [MGA inks new marine capacity deal with Intact Insurance](https://www.insurancetimes.